comments: How much time will Julia take to overtake Python, in terms of being "widely used for everything & Variety in Packages"?
reply:
It's catching up really fast. Developing new libraries in Julia is quite easy thanks to multiple dispatch and generic code. It also has a great built in package manager that makes creating tests and docs super easy.

I reckon within the next 5 years it'll start eating Python's lunch for sure. Some of the shit in Julia is already much more powerful and fast than the Python alternatives. For example, DifferentialEquations.jl (differential equations including ODEs, PDEs, Algebraic DEs, Neural DEs, Stochastic DEs), JuMP.jl (optimisation), Flux.jl (neural networks).

comments: the dot vector syntax like x.*2 and function piping like x |> sqrt |> sum is also very nice feature of Julia
reply:
@Mr Octo the dot syntax means to peform an operation for every element of an array instead the array itself, array.map in other languages. For example, in javascript, if you want to create an array where every element is the element of an old array + 5, you would do something like:

let newArray = oldArray.map(x => x + 5)

The equivalent julia code is:

newArray = map(x -> x + 5, oldArray)

But you can use dot syntax to "broadcast" the operation for every element of the oldArray, like this:

newArray = oldArray .+ 5

This is a much more cleaner syntax.

comments: the dot vector syntax like x.*2 and function piping like x |> sqrt |> sum is also very nice feature of Julia
reply:
@Mr Octo the dot in X.*2 is a shortcut for broadcasting. If you search for broadcasting in Julia you will learn a lot more about it.

Basically it stands for: multiply every element in the vector by 2

What's the difference between dispatching and function overloading?
reply:
It's not the same, in Java for example yes you can have multiple functions with the same name but different argument types (overloading), but when you invoke such function you explicitly need to say which one you want to use, you can't simple pass generic types, the code will not compile.

With multiple dispatch, like in Julia, you don't need to specify, you just pass an object and in runtime the correct function is selected (this is multiple dispatch, which Java doesn't support) .

comments: What's the difference between dispatching and function overloading?
reply: ‚Äã@J V Ah. Thank you. At least there is a difference. And now we know it's safe to think of them as essentially the same.

comments: What's the difference between dispatching and function overloading?
reply: I looked it up.  I can't link the software engineering stack overflow post here w/o being reported as spam, so I'll summarize:  dispatching is for dynamic types (types that can change at runtime).  Overloading is only for static types (so like Java).  this seems like a weird difference to have a whole new confusing term for.

class(type) function

we have:

struct(type) function
-fields(data) -methods(behavior)

comments: Multiple dispatch? so... Method overloading?
reply: The difference is that method overloading requires static types to figure out at compile time which methods should be called, however multiple dispatch happens at runtime. And even though you can type-anotate the arguments of your function, that only tells the compiler which optimizations to make for that type. For example, one thing you can do in julia is to define your own number type with something like `struct MyNumber <: Number end` and just define some base methods for `MyNumber`, the instances of it will magically behave like a julia Number.

reply:
The main advantage of Julia, apart from speed, is code re-use. Case in point, I wanted to use an automatic differentiation library with an interval arithmetic library. Because the autodiff library works works on the Real supertype, interval arithmetic works seamlessly with it even though the two Julia packages themselves are written independently.

Very often, everything "just works". When it doesn't, you can define new methods without breaking existing functionality. Try to do that in an object-oriented language without having to define a bunch of new methods for your object.

comments: Never heard of Julia before but want to learn it right now
reply: @DragonFighter603 Because Julia puts a lot of stress on readability and the "end" keyword is part of that. It looks weird at first, but when you get into it it makes a lot of sense. For one thing, curly braces get reserved for some parts of type declaration, and so using them for functions and structs and stuff would get confusing very easily. Also, having "end" gives the benefits of python's "plain English" appearance without succumbing to the royal pain that is indentation errors. There are also benefits in that it makes Julia look a bit distinctive, although that is a minor benefit. Overall, "end" just makes sense for Julia and the way it is intended to be used
